  "rollout_plan": 0,
  "rollout_plan_displayname": "Will ship enabled for all users",
  "motivation": "Developers wish to have control over the resources loaded into their pages' contexts and the endpoints to which their pages can make requests. This control is necessary for several purposes, including limiting the ways in which users' data can flow through the user agent (mitigating exfiltration attacks) and ensuring control over a site’s architecture and dependencies.\n\nContent Security Policy addresses some of this need, but does so in a way that is more granular than necessary for the most critical use cases, and with a syntax and grammar that’s complicated by the other protections CSP is used to deploy.\n\n`Connection-Allowlist` steps back from CSP, and focuses on the single use case of controlling the explicit requests a page may initiate through Fetch and other web platform APIs (Navigations, preload, DNS Prefetch, WebRTC, Web Transport, etc) in a way that aims to be straightforward and comprehensive.\n\nExample:\nConnection-Allowlist: (response-origin \"https://cdn.example\" \"https://*.example.:tld\" \\\n                       \"https://api.example:*\"); report-to=ReportingAPIEndpoint\n",
  "devtrial_instructions": null,
  "activation_risks": "No challenges for developers to take advantage of this feature immediately.",
  "measurement": "UseCounter has been added for measuring the usage of the feature",
  "availability_expectation": "Feature is available only in Chromium browsers for the foreseeable future.",
  "adoption_expectation": "Feature is used by specific partner(s) to provide functionality within 12 months of launch in Chrome.",
  "adoption_plan": "Some of the partners are already participating in the Origin Trial and they are expected to adopt the feature as it ships in Chrome.\nThe use counter can be seen here: https://chromestatus.com/metrics/feature/timeline/popularity/5867",
  "initial_public_proposal_url": "https://github.com/WICG/proposals/issues/235",
  "explainer_links": [
    "https://github.com/WICG/connection-allowlists"
  ],
  "requires_embedder_support": true,
  "spec_link": "https://wicg.github.io/connection-allowlists",
  "api_spec": false,
  "automation_spec": false,
  "interop_compat_risks": "This is a new feature. We are interacting with other browsers via discussions on GitHub and in the Community Group. However, there is no  official signal yet from any other browser vendors about their implementation plans.",
  "all_platforms": true,
  "all_platforms_descr": null,
  "non_oss_deps": "None",
  "anticipated_spec_changes": "https://github.com/WICG/connection-allowlists/issues\n \nNote that issues marked as enhancement, like https://github.com/WICG/connection-allowlists/issues/1, https://github.com/WICG/connection-allowlists/issues/28 are not included in this entry and will be launched via a separate I2S, but are additive and backward-compatible.",
  "security_risks": "This feature should be beneficial for security because it allows documents and workers to restrict network communication that could exfiltrate sensitive data. \n\n",
  "ergonomics_risks": "This feature will be frequently used in tandem with existing Web Platform Security mechanisms like Content Security Policy, Sandbox etc.\nWe expect no impact on Chrome's performance.",
  "wpt": true,
  "wpt_descr": "https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/tree/master/connection-allowlist/tentative",
  "webview_risks": "No. This is a new feature.",
  "devrel_emails": [
    "devrel-chromestatus-all@google.com"
  ],
  "debuggability": "To assist developers in debugging malformed headers, parsing errors are reported directly to the DevTools Issues tab. \n\nAdditionally, the reporting infrastructure for Connection-Allowlist was introduced to support both enforced violation reporting and a \"report-only\" mode, allowing developers to monitor potential breakages without interrupting service.\n",
